# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anchor-brewing-company
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The **16th Avenue Tiled Steps**, colloquially known as the **Moraga Steps**, is a stairway in the Golden Gate Heights neighborhood on the West Side of San Francisco, California.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] *Fodor's* calls it "possibly the world's largest mosaic staircase", and it leads up to Grandview Park.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The flight contains 163 steps stretching 90 feet (27 m) high.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] These steps are also covered in over 2,000 unique tiles from over 75,000 glass fragments.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Inspired by the Escadaria Selarón in Brazil, the project was first pitched by two residents of the neighborhood, Jessie Audette and Alice Yee Xavier in 2003.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The duo tried to find a way to link all their neighbors together in an effort to enrich the area.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Aileen Barr and Colette Crutcher, who also designed the nearby Hidden Garden Steps six years later, were chosen by residents to plan the panels of the mosaics.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The project was funded by over 220 sponsored/named tiles which were also placed on the staircase.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Community members all pitched in to create panels together, and three workshops were held.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The Mayor's Neighborhood Beautification Fund also donated to the construction effort.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The opening ceremony was held on August 27, 2005, featuring lion dancers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Francesco Pignataro, the then-mayor of Caltagirone, Italy, also attended, as the steps' sister, Staircase of Santa Maria del Monte, was located there.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Acting Mayor and member of the Board of Supervisors Sean Elsbernd declared August 27 as 16th Avenue Tiled Steps Day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Areas nearby the steps rose in crime during 2016, as car robbers took advantage of the tourists viewing the steps to break in.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] Both sides of the stairs contain a garden containing native California plants (which support the endangered green hairstreak) and succulents, with the south side being donated by the Xavier family, while the north side was developed in 2006, after a grant was obtained from San Francisco Beautiful.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The San Francisco Succulent Society donated succulents in 2010, and Nature in the City helped with a restoration of the butterfly habitats in 2014.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] One Brick assists in organizing volunteering days, which occur on Earth Day weekend and fall.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/16th-avenue-tiled-steps] The stairs themselves have a design focused on the sky and sea, with sea creatures containing names of sponsors dotted within.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] PDT, the **Loma Prieta earthquake** occurred on the Central Coast of California.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The shock was centered in The Forest of Nisene Marks State Park in Santa Cruz County, approximately 10 mi (16 km) northeast of Santa Cruz on a section of the San Andreas Fault System and was named for the nearby Loma Prieta Peak in the Santa Cruz Mountains.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] With an Mw magnitude of 6.9 and a maximum Modified Mercalli intensity of IX (*Violent*), the shock was responsible for 63 deaths and 3,757 injuries.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Loma Prieta segment of the San Andreas Fault System had been relatively inactive since the 1906 San Francisco earthquake (to the degree that it was designated a seismic gap) until two moderate foreshocks occurred in June 1988 and again in August 1989.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Damage was heavy in Santa Cruz County and less so to the south in Monterey County, but effects extended well to the north into the San Francisco Bay Area, both on the San Francisco Peninsula and across the bay in Oakland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] No surface faulting occurred, though many other ground failures and landslides were present, especially in the Summit area of the Santa Cruz Mountains.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Liquefaction was also a significant issue, especially in the heavily damaged Marina District of San Francisco, but its effects were also seen in the East Bay, and near the shore of Monterey Bay, where a non-destructive tsunami was also observed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The collapse of a section of the double-deck Nimitz Freeway in Oakland was the site of the largest number of casualties for the event, but the collapse of human-made structures and other related accidents contributed to casualties occurring in San Francisco, Los Gatos, and Santa Cruz.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The history of earthquake investigations in California has been largely focused on the San Andreas Fault system because of its strong influence in the state as the boundary between the Pacific plate and the North American plate; it is the most studied fault on Earth.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Andrew Lawson, a geologist from the University of California, Berkeley, had named the fault after the San Andreas Lake (prior to the occurrence of the 1906 San Francisco earthquake) and later led an investigation into that event.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The San Andreas Fault ruptured for a length of 290 mi (470 km) during the 1906 shock, both to the north of San Francisco and to the south in the Santa Cruz Mountains region.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Several long term forecasts for a large shock along the San Andreas Fault in that area had been made public prior to 1989 (the event and its aftershocks occurred within a recognized seismic gap) but the earthquake that transpired was not what had been anticipated.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The 1989 Loma Prieta event originated on an undiscovered oblique-slip reverse fault that is located adjacent to the San Andreas Fault.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Since many forecasts had been presented for the region near Loma Prieta, seismologists were not taken by surprise by the October 1989 event.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Between 1910 and 1989 there were 20 widely varying forecasts that were announced, with some that were highly specific, covering multiple aspects of an event, while others were less complete and vague.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] An updated forecast was presented in 1988, at which time Lindh took the opportunity to assign a new name to the San Juan Bautista segment – the Loma Prieta segment.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The thirty year probability for one or more M7 earthquakes in the study area was given as 50%, but because of a lack of information and low confidence, a 30% probability was assigned to the Southern Santa Cruz Mountains segment.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Two moderate shocks, referred to as the Lake Elsman earthquakes by the USGS, occurred in the Santa Cruz Mountains region in June 1988 and again in August 1989.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Following each event, the State office of Emergency Services issued (for the first time in Bay Area history) short term advisories for a possible large earthquake, which meant there was "a slightly increased likelihood of an M6.5 event on the Santa Cruz Mountains segment of the San Andreas fault".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The advisories following the two Lake Elsman events were issued in part because of the statements made by WGCEP and because they were two of the three largest shocks to occur along the 1906 earthquake's rupture zone since 1914.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The ML 5.3 June 1988 and the ML 5.4 August 1989 events also occurred on previously unknown oblique reverse faults and were within 3 mi (4.8 km) of the M6.9 Loma Prieta mainshock epicenter, near the intersection of the San Andreas and Sargent faults.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Each event's aftershock sequence and effect on stress drop was closely examined, and their study indicated that the shocks affected the mainshock's rupture process.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Following the August 8, 1989, shock, in anticipation of an upcoming large earthquake, staff at the University of California, Santa Cruz deployed four accelerometers in the area, which were positioned at the UCSC campus, two residences in Santa Cruz, and a home in Los Gatos.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Unlike other nearby (high gain) seismographs that were overwhelmed (driven off scale) by the large magnitude mainshock, the four accelerometers captured a useful record of the main event and more than half an hour of the early aftershock activity.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The June 27, 1988, shock occurred with a maximum intensity of VI (*Strong*).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Its effects included broken windows in Los Gatos, and other light damage in Holy City, where increased flow was observed at a water well.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Farther away from the Santa Cruz Mountains, pieces of concrete fell from a parking structure at the Sunnyvale Town Center, a two-level shopping mall in Santa Clara County.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] More moderate damage resulted from the August 8, 1989, shock (intensity VII, *Very strong*) when chimneys were toppled in Cupertino, Los Gatos, and Redwood Estates.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other damage included cracked walls and foundations and broken underground pipes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At the office of the Los Gatos City Manager, a window that was cracked had also been broken in the earlier shock.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Also in Los Gatos, one man died when he fell or jumped through a window and impacted the ground five stories below.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Loma Prieta earthquake was named for Loma Prieta Peak in the Santa Cruz Mountains, which lies just to the east of the mainshock epicenter.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The duration of the heaviest shaking in the Santa Cruz Mountains was about 15 seconds, but strong ground motion recordings revealed that the duration of shaking was not uniform throughout the affected area (because of different types and thicknesses of soil).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At sites with rocky terrain, the duration was shorter and the shaking was much less intense, and at locations with unconsolidated soil (like the Marina District in San Francisco or the Cypress Street Viaduct in Oakland) the intensity of the shaking was more severe and lasted longer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The strong motion records also allowed for the causative fault to be determined – the rupture was related to the San Andreas Fault System.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] While a Mercalli Intensity of VIII (*Severe*) covered a large swath of territory relatively close to the epicenter (including the cities of Los Gatos, Santa Cruz, and Watsonville) farther to the north, portions of San Francisco were assessed at intensity IX (*Violent*).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At more than 44 miles (70 km) distant, the San Francisco Bay Area recorded peak horizontal accelerations that were as high as 0.26 *g*, and close to the epicenter they peaked at more than 0.6 *g*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In a general way, the location of aftershocks of the event delineated the extent of the faulting, which (according to seismologist Bruce Bolt) extended about 24 miles (40 km) in length.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because the rupture took place bilaterally, the duration of strong shaking was about half of what it would have been had it ruptured in one direction only.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The duration of a typical M6.9 shock with a comparable rupture length would have been about twice as long.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Gregory Beroza, a seismologist with Stanford University, made several distinctions regarding the 1906 and 1989 events.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Near Loma Prieta, the 1906 rupture was more shallow, had more strike-slip, and occurred on a fault that was near vertical.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The 1989 event's oblique-slip rupture was at 10 km and below on a fault plane that dipped 70° to the southwest.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because much of the slip in 1989 occurred at depth and the rupture propagated up dip, Beroza proposed that the overlying San Andreas Fault actually inhibited further rupture and also maintains that the occurrence of an event at the location that was forecast by the WGCEP in 1988 was coincidental.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The contrasting characteristics of the 1906 and 1989 events were examined by seismologists Hiroo Kanamori and Kenji Satake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The significant amount of vertical displacement in 1989 was a key aspect to consider because a long-term sequence of 1989-type events (with an 80–100-year recurrence interval) normally result in regions with high topographic relief, which is not seen in the Santa Cruz Mountains.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Three scenarios were presented that might explain this disparity.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The first is that the geometry of the San Andreas Fault goes through a transition every several thousand years.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Secondly, slip type could vary from event to event.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] And lastly, the 1989 event did not occur on the San Andreas Fault.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] While the effects of a four-year drought limited the potential of landslides, the steep terrain near the epicenter was prone to movement, and up to 4,000 landslides may have occurred during the event.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The majority of landslides occurred to the southwest of the epicenter, especially along road cuts in the Santa Cruz Mountains and in the Summit Road area, but also along the bluffs of the Pacific Coast, and as far north as the Marin Peninsula.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Highway 17 was blocked for several weeks by a large slide and one person was killed by a rockfall along the coast.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other areas with certain soil conditions were susceptible to site amplification due to the effects of liquefaction, especially near the shore of San Francisco Bay (where its effects were severe in the Marina District) and to the west of the epicenter near rivers and other bodies of water.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Minor lateral spreading was also seen along the shores of San Francisco Bay and to the south near Monterey Bay.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other ground effects included downslope movement, slumps, and ground cracks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Fifty-seven of the deaths were directly caused by the earthquake; six further fatalities were ruled to have been caused indirectly.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In addition, there were 3,757 injuries as a result of the earthquake, 400 of which were serious.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The highest number of deaths, 42, occurred in Oakland because of the collapse of the Cypress Street Viaduct on the Nimitz Freeway (Interstate 880), where the upper level of a double-deck portion of the freeway collapsed, crushing the cars on the lower level, and causing crashes on the upper level.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] One 50-foot (15 m) section of the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge also collapsed, leading to a single fatality, Anamafi Moala, a 23-year-old woman.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Three people were killed in the collapse of buildings along the Pacific Garden Mall in Santa Cruz, and five people were killed in the collapse of a brick wall on Bluxome Street in San Francisco.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake hit, the third game of the 1989 World Series baseball championship was about to begin.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because of the unusual circumstance that both of the World Series teams (the San Francisco Giants and Oakland Athletics) were based in the affected area, many people had left work early or were staying late to participate in after work group viewings and parties.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] As a consequence the normally crowded freeways contained unusually light traffic.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] If traffic had been normal for a Tuesday rush hour, injuries and deaths would certainly have been higher.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The initial media reports failed to take into account the game's effect on traffic and initially estimated the death toll at 300, a number that was corrected to 63 in the days after the earthquake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After the earthquake occurred, a group led by Antony C.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Fraser-Smith of Stanford University reported that the event was preceded by disturbances in background magnetic field noise as measured by a sensor placed in Corralitos, about 4.5 miles (7 km) from the epicenter.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] From October 5, they reported that a substantial increase in noise was measured in the frequency range 0.01–10 Hz.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The measurement instrument was a single-axis search-coil magnetometer that was being used for low frequency research.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Precursor increases of noise apparently started a few days before the earthquake, with noise in the range 0.01–0.5 Hz rising to exceptionally high levels about three hours before the earthquake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Fraser-Smith et al. report remains one of the most frequently cited claims of a specific earthquake precursor; more recent studies have cast doubt on the connection, attributing the Corralitos signals to either unrelated magnetic disturbance or, even more simply, to sensor-system malfunction.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The earthquake caused severe damage in some very specific locations in the Bay Area, most notably on unstable soil in San Francisco and Oakland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Oakland City Hall was evacuated after the earthquake until a US$80 million (equivalent to US$208 million today) seismic retrofit and hazard abatement work was completed in 1995.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many other communities sustained severe damage throughout the region located in Alameda, San Mateo, Santa Clara, San Benito, Santa Cruz and Monterey counties.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Major property damage in San Francisco's Marina District 60 mi (97 km) from the epicenter resulted from liquefaction of soil used to create waterfront land.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Other effects included sand volcanoes, landslides and ground ruptures.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Some 12,000 homes and 2,600 businesses were damaged.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) turned people who were homeless prior to the earthquake away from homeless shelters and provided shelter for those with homes prior to the earthquake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In Santa Cruz, close to the epicenter, 40 buildings collapsed, killing six people.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At the Santa Cruz Beach Boardwalk, the Plunge Building was significantly damaged.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Liquefaction also caused damage in the Watsonville area.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] For example, sand volcanoes formed in a field near Pajaro as well as in a strawberry field.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Ford's department store in Watsonville experienced significant damage, including a crack down the front of the building.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many homes were dislodged if they were not bolted to their foundations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] There were structural failures of twin bridges across Struve Slough near Watsonville.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In Moss Landing, the liquefaction destroyed the causeway that carried the Moss Beach access road across a tidewater basin, damaged the approach and abutment of the bridge linking Moss Landing spit to the mainland and cracked the paved road on Paul's Island.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In the Old Town historical district of the city of Salinas, unreinforced masonry buildings were partially destroyed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Following the quake, an estimated 1.4 million people experienced power losses that were mainly due to damaged electrical substations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many San Francisco radio and television stations were temporarily knocked off the air.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KGO-TV, the local ABC station in San Francisco, was off the air for about 15 minutes, while KRON-TV (at the time the region's NBC affiliate) was off the air for about half an hour, and KGO-AM (ABC News Radio) was off the air for about 40 minutes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] About an hour and 40 minutes after the quake, Fox affiliate KTVU resumed broadcasting, with their news anchors, Dennis Richmond and Elaine Corral reporting from the station's parking lot.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KCBS-AM (CBS News Radio) switched immediately to backup power and managed to stay on air despite a subsequent generator failure.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KCBS later won a Peabody Award for their news coverage, as did KGO-TV.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The malfunctions during the aftermath of the earthquake caused confusion as to whether an earthquake would cause the Emergency Broadcast System to activate.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KNBR began using an emergency generator, hooking up the signal from a command center right after their nearby studio was severely shaken during the quake, when most of the KNBR staff were at Candlestick for the World Series.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Mayor of San Francisco, Art Agnos, later came on the air and provided an update on the earthquake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Power was restored to most of San Francisco by midnight, and all but 12,000 customers had their power restored within two days.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The quake caused an estimated $6 billion (equivalent to $16 billion today) in property damage, becoming one of the most expensive natural disasters in U.S. history at the time.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Private donations poured into aid relief efforts and on October 26, President George H.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Bush signed a $1.1 billion ($2.9 billion today) earthquake relief package for California.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Four people died in San Francisco's Marina District, four buildings were destroyed by fire, and seven buildings collapsed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Another 63 damaged structures were judged too dangerous to live in.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Among the four deaths, one family lost their infant son who choked on dust while trapped for an hour inside their collapsed apartment.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The Marina district was built on a landfill made of a mixture of sand, dirt, rubble, waste, and other materials containing a high percentage of groundwater.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Some of the fill was rubble dumped into San Francisco Bay after the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, but most was sand and debris laid down in preparation for the 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition, a celebration of San Francisco's ability to rebound after its catastrophe in 1906.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After the Exposition, apartment buildings were erected on the landfill.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In the 1989 earthquake, the water-saturated unconsolidated mud, sand, and rubble suffered liquefaction, and the earthquake's vertical shock waves rippled the ground more severely.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] At the intersection of Beach and Divisadero Streets in San Francisco, a natural gas main rupture caused a major structure fire.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The San Francisco Fire Department selected civilians to help run fire hoses from a distance because the nearby hydrant system failed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Since the bay was only two blocks from the burning buildings, water from the bay was pumped by the fireboat *Phoenix*, to engines on the shore, and from there sprayed on the fire.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The apartment structures that collapsed were older buildings that included ground-floor garages, which engineers refer to as a soft story building.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In Santa Cruz, the Pacific Garden Mall was severely damaged, with falling debris killing three people, half of the six earthquake deaths in Santa Cruz and Monterey Counties.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Some 31 buildings were damaged enough to warrant demolition, seven of which had been listed in the Santa Cruz Historic Building Survey.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The four oldest were built in 1894, the five oldest withstood the 1906 San Francisco earthquake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Immediately, a number of civilians began to free victims from the rubble of Ford's Department Store and the Santa Cruz Coffee Roasting Company – both buildings had collapsed inward on customers and employees alike.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Two police officers crawled through voids in the debris, found one victim alive and another dead inside the coffee house.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Santa Cruz beach lifeguards assisted in moving the victims.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Police dogs were brought in to help locate other victims.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The civilians who were helpful initially, were soon viewed by police and fire officials as a hindrance to operations, with frantic coworkers and friends of a coffee house employee thought to be trapped under the rubble continuing their efforts in the dark.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Police arrested those who refused to stop searching.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] This became a political issue in the following days.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The body of a young woman coffee worker was found under a collapsed wall late the next day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] During the first few days following the quake, electric power to most Santa Cruz County subscribers was out, and some areas had no water.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Limited phone service remained online, providing a crucial link to rescue workers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Widespread search operations were organized to find possible victims inside the remains of fallen structures.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] As many as six teams of dogs and their handlers were at work identifying the large number of damaged buildings that held no victims.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The quake claimed one life in Watsonville: a driver who collided with panicked horses after they escaped their collapsed corral.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In other Santa Cruz and Monterey county locations such as Boulder Creek and Moss Landing, a number of structures were damaged, with some knocked off of their foundations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Many residents slept outside their homes out of concern for further damage from aftershocks, of which there were 51 with magnitudes greater than 3.0 in the following 24 hours, and 16 more the second day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The earthquake damaged several historic buildings in the Old Town district of Salinas, and some were later demolished.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Damage to the Salinas River rail bridge and subsequent repairs led to reduced traffic on the Monterey Branch Line, which contributed to the discontinuance of freight rail services in western Monterey County.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge suffered severe damage, as a 76-by-50-foot (23 m × 15 m) section of the upper deck on the eastern cantilever side fell onto the deck below.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The quake caused the Oakland side of the bridge to shift 7 in (18 cm) to the east, and caused the bolts of one section to shear off, sending the 250-short-ton (230 t; 500,000 lb; 226,800 kg) section of roadbed crashing down like a trapdoor.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Traffic on both decks came to a halt, blocked by the section of the roadbed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Police began unsnarling the traffic jam, telling drivers to turn their cars around and drive back the way they had come.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Eastbound drivers stuck on the lower deck between the collapse and Yerba Buena Island were routed up to the upper deck and westward back to San Francisco.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] A miscommunication made by emergency workers at Yerba Buena Island routed some drivers the wrong way; they were directed to the upper deck where they drove eastward toward the collapse site.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] One of these drivers did not see the open gap in time; the 1980 Mercury Zephyr plunged over the edge and smashed onto the collapsed roadbed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The driver, Anamafi Moala, died, and the passenger, her brother, was seriously injured.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The family sued the state for their role in Moala's death.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Caltrans removed and replaced the collapsed section, and re-opened the bridge on November 18.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] To assist with transportation during Bay Bridge repairs, Bay Area Rapid Transit ran 24-hour service in the Transbay Tube between the date of the earthquake and December 3 that same year.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The worst disaster of the earthquake was the collapse of the double-deck Cypress Street Viaduct of Interstate 880 in West Oakland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The failure of a 1.25-mile (2.0 km) section of the viaduct, also known as the "Cypress Structure" and the "Cypress Freeway", killed 42 and injured many more.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Built in the late 1950s and opened to traffic in 1957 (as SR 17), the Cypress Street Viaduct, a stretch of Interstate 880, was a double-deck freeway section made of nonductile reinforced concrete that was constructed above and astride Cypress Street in Oakland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Roughly half of the land the Cypress Viaduct was built on was filled marshland and the other half somewhat more stable alluvium.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Because of new highway structure design guidelines – the requirement of ductile construction elements – instituted following the 1971 San Fernando earthquake, a limited degree of earthquake reinforcement was retrofitted to the Cypress Viaduct in 1977.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The added elements were longitudinal restraints at transverse expansion joints in the box girder spans, but no studies were made of possible failure modes specific to the Cypress Viaduct.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Caltrans has since received widespread backlash for not thoroughly studying the structure.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake hit, the shaking was amplified on the former marshland, and soil liquefaction occurred.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake struck, the freeway buckled and twisted before the support columns failed and the upper deck fell on the lower deck.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Forty-two people were crushed to death in their cars.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Cars on the upper deck were tossed around violently, some of them flipped sideways, and some were left dangling at the edge of the freeway.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Nearby residents and factory workers came to the rescue, climbing onto the wreckage with ladders and forklifts and pulling trapped people out of their cars from under a four-foot gap in some sections.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] 60 members of Oakland's Public Works Agency left the nearby city yard and joined rescue efforts.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Employees from Pacific Pipe drove heavy lift equipment to the scene and started using it to raise sections of fallen freeway enough to allow further rescue.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Local workers continued their volunteer operation nonstop until October 21, 1989, when they were forced to pause as U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Bush and California Governor George Deukmejian viewed the damage.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] That same day, survivor Buck Helm was freed from the wreckage, having spent 90 hours trapped in his car.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Dubbed "Lucky Buck" by the local radio, Helm lived for another 29 days on life support, but then died of respiratory failure at the age of 58.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Although the freeway reopened in stages between 1997 and 1999, it was not fully rebuilt until 2001 so that it would comply with safety and reinforcement standards.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] In the meantime, traffic was detoured through nearby Interstate 980, causing increased congestion.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Street-level Mandela Parkway now occupies the previous roadbed of the Cypress structure.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Immediately after the earthquake, Bay Area airports were closed so officials could conduct a visual inspection and damage assessment procedures.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] San Jose International Airport, Oakland International Airport and San Francisco International Airport all opened the next morning.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Large cracks in Oakland's runway and taxiway reduced the usable length to two-thirds normal, and damage to the dike required quick remediation to avoid flooding the runway with water from the bay.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Oakland Airport repair costs were assessed at $30 million (equivalent to $82 million today).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] San Francisco Municipal Railway (Muni) lost all power to electric transit systems when the quake hit, but otherwise suffered little damage and no injuries to operators or riders.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Cable cars and electric trains and buses were stalled in place – half of Muni's transport capability was lost for 12 hours.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Muni resorted to Diesel-powered buses to continue abbreviated service until electric power was restored later that night, and electric units could be inspected and readied for service on the morning of October 18.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After 78 hours, 96 percent of Muni services were back in operation, including the cable cars.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Amtrak intercity rail service into Oakland from the *California Zephyr* continued, but the *Coast Starlight* was temporarily suspended north of Salinas because of damage to the Southern Pacific Railroad's Coast Line.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The earthquake changed the Bay Area's automobile transportation landscape.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Not only did the quake force seismic retrofitting of all Bay Area bridges, it caused enough damage that some parts of the region's freeway system had to be demolished.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Damage to the region's transportation system was estimated at $1.8 billion (equivalent to $4.7 billion today).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The 1989 World Series featured the Oakland Athletics and the San Francisco Giants in the first cross-town World Series since 1956.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Game 3 of the series was scheduled to begin at San Francisco's Candlestick Park on October 17 at 5:35 PDT, and American television network ABC began its pre-game show at 5:00 PDT.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When the earthquake struck at approximately 5:04 PDT, sportscaster Tim McCarver was narrating taped highlights of Game 2, which had been played two days prior across the Bay Bridge in Oakland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Television viewers saw the video signal begin to break up, heard McCarver repeat a sentence as the shaking distracted him, and heard McCarver's colleague Al Michaels exclaim, "I'll tell you what, we're having an earth – ." At that moment, the signal from Candlestick Park was lost.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The combined screams of excitement and panic from fans who had no idea of the devastation elsewhere could be heard in the background.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The first television news report of the earthquake, filed by reporter Mark Coogan, came over KABC-TV in Los Angeles at 5:11 p.m.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KGO-TV, the local owned-and-operated ABC station in San Francisco, lost power for almost 15 minutes upon the start of the earthquake, before beginning its coverage with anchor Cheryl Jennings.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] On KGO-TV's feed during the outage, the network's "World Series" telop graphic was replaced with a station identification slide, recycled from the network's 1986-87 "Together" campaign, with "Please Stand By" text on top of the Circle 7 logo.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] With anchorman Ted Koppel in position in Washington, D.C., ABC News began continuous coverage of the quake at 5:32 p.m.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] PDT, with Al Michaels, in the process, becoming a de facto on-site reporter for ABC.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] CBS News also began coverage around that same time with coverage from its San Francisco affiliate KPIX-TV.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] About an hour later, NBC News also began continuous coverage with Tom Brokaw anchoring and featuring local coverage from its then-San Francisco affiliate, KRON-TV.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] A Goodyear Blimp had already been overhead to cover the baseball game, and ABC used it to capture images of damage to the Bay Bridge and other locations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Local Fox affiliate KTVU was knocked off the air for over 90 minutes before returning to the air with a raw feed fed from one of the station's remote trucks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] KTVU anchors Dennis Richmond and Elaine Corral began their coverage from the station's parking lot, as power had not yet been restored to that section of Oakland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Inside Candlestick Park, fewer than half of the more than 62,000 fans had reached their seats by the time of the quake, and the load on the structure of the stadium was lower than maximum.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] There had also been a seismic-strengthening project previously completed on the upper deck concrete windscreen that may have prevented large numbers of injuries in the event of serious damage or even a catastrophic collapse.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Fans reported that the stadium moved in an articulated manner as the earthquake wave passed through it, that the light standards swayed by many feet, and that the concrete upper deck windscreen moved in a wave-like manner over a distance of several feet.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] When electrical power to the stadium was lost, someone drove a police car onto the field, where an officer used the car's public address system to advise that the game had been postponed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After the shaking subsided, many of the players on both teams immediately searched for, and gathered, family and friends from the stands before evacuating the facility.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The October 18, 1989, edition of NBC's *Today* that covered the earthquake ran until noon Eastern Time.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Bryant Gumbel, Jane Pauley and Deborah Norville anchored from Chicago (where they had planned to originally do a special celebratory edition), with reports done by Bob Jamieson and Don Oliver in San Francisco, and George Lewis in Oakland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] Jim Miklaszewski and Bob Hager covered disaster response from Washington.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] NBC Sports commentators Bob Costas and Jimmy Cefalo discussed the effect the temblor would have on the 1989 World Series.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] The World Series was delayed while the Bay Area started the recovery process.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] While the teams' stadiums had suffered only minor damage, it took several days for power and transmission links at Candlestick Park to be repaired.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] After ten days (the longest delay in World Series history), Game 3 was held in San Francisco on October 27, with the Athletics defeating the Giants 13–7; the Athletics then completed the four-game sweep the following afternoon with a 9–6 victory in Game 4.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] It is likely that the World Series game saved many lives, as Bay Area residents who would have normally been on the freeways were at home ready to watch the game when the earthquake hit.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/1989-loma-prieta-earthquake] It is a rough estimate that thousands of people may have otherwise been on the Cypress Structure during the 5:00 p.m. rush-hour, as the structure was said to have carried 195,000 vehicles a day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The **49-Mile Scenic Drive** is a historic scenic road tour highlighting much of San Francisco, California.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] It was created in 1938 by the San Francisco Down Town Association to showcase the city's major attractions and natural beauty during the 1939 Golden Gate International Exposition.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Originally beginning at San Francisco City Hall and ending on Treasure Island, the route has been modified several times since.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] By 1999, the route formed a loop proceeding counterclockwise from Civic Center Plaza, and its length was closer to 48.8 miles (78.5 km).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Modern signage for the route, depicting a seagull in profile on a sky blue background, was erected in 1954 and is maintained by the San Francisco Department of Parking and Traffic.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Owing variously to its length, its labyrinthine route, and the difficulty of driving through a bustling city, the drive remained relatively unpopular with tourists and locals alike.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Permanent closures to vehicular traffic on John F.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Kennedy Drive in Golden Gate Park and on Great Highway in the 2020s made the loop discontinuous.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 2019, the *San Francisco Chronicle* proposed a non-driving alternative that it called the **49-Mile Scenic Route**.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The drive begins on Polk Street opposite San Francisco City Hall.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Circling Civic Center Plaza and passing Bill Graham Civic Auditorium, the San Francisco Public Library's main branch, and the Asian Art Museum, the route continues north along Larkin Street through Little Saigon before turning onto Geary Boulevard and proceeding west up Cathedral Hill.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] After entering Japantown, the drive turns north onto Webster Street before immediately returning east along Post Street, where it continues past Japan Center, Lower Nob Hill, and Union Square.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Grant Avenue, the route again turns north and enters Chinatown through its Dragon Gate.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Drivers are soon directed onto California Street and up Nob Hill, passing its landmark hotels.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning north at Grace Cathedral, the route then directs drivers east onto Washington Street, passing the San Francisco Cable Car Museum, then south onto Powell Street for one block before descending east along Clay Street, back into Chinatown.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Portsmouth Square, the route proceeds north along Kearny Street for two blocks and turns northwest onto Columbus Avenue, entering North Beach.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] After passing City Lights Bookstore and turning onto Grant Avenue once more, the route travels for six blocks up Telegraph Hill before turning west onto Lombard Street near Coit Tower.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Passing the Joe DiMaggio Playground, the route turns north toward Fisherman's Wharf on Mason Street.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Jefferson Street, the route proceeds alongside the waterfront—passing Aquatic Park and the San Francisco Maritime Museum with several quick turns heading into the Marina District near Fort Mason.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Over the next few miles, the route passes nearly all of San Francisco's Golden Gate National Recreation Area locations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route detours through the Marina Green parking lot and takes a path of residential streets to the Palace of Fine Arts, the most prominent remaining structure from the 1915 Panama–Pacific International Exposition.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Continuing for a few blocks each on Baker, Bay, Broderick, Chestnut, and Lyon streets, the route enters the Presidio at Lombard Street.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] At 8.6 miles (13.8 km), the route passes the Letterman Digital Arts Center, proceeds onto Presidio Boulevard, and continues onto Lincoln Boulevard.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route detours through the Presidio's Main Post before returning to Lincoln Boulevard near San Francisco National Cemetery.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Passing above Crissy Field and Fort Point, under the U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Highway 101 (US 101) approach to the Golden Gate Bridge, and above Baker Beach, the route exits the Presidio into Sea Cliff.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Continuing along El Camino del Mar into Lincoln Park, the route passes the Legion of Honor and exits the park into the Richmond District.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning westward onto Geary Boulevard, drivers proceed several blocks and continue onto Point Lobos Avenue, soon reaching the Sutro Baths and Cliff House.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route then enters Golden Gate Park and winds through it for about 5 miles (8.0 km)—circling Stow Lake; passing the Japanese Tea Garden, San Francisco Botanical Garden, and California Academy of Sciences; turning at the AIDS Memorial Grove; and exiting the park's East Portal at Stanyan Street.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Briefly skirting the Haight-Ashbury and Cole Valley neighborhoods, the route ascends Parnassus Street and passes the University of California, San Francisco's main campus.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning south onto 7th Avenue in the Inner Sunset, the route curves around Mount Sutro and the Laguna Honda Reservoir before turning east and climbing Twin Peaks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] From Twin Peaks Boulevard, drivers are directed into the north peak's parking area and offered unobstructed views of the city below.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route then descends into Corona Heights—built to take full advantage of the views at this height.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Winding its way down the hill, the route takes drivers past the Randall Museum before descending east along 14th Street into San Francisco's prominent gay neighborhood, The Castro.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Now 36.6 miles (58.9 km) into the drive, the route turns southward along tree-lined Dolores Street, passing Mission San Francisco de Asís and Mission Dolores Park while splitting the Castro, Mission District, and Noe Valley en route to Cesar Chavez Street.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Cesar Chavez Street, the route continues east through Potrero Hill before abruptly directing drivers onto northbound I-280.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] After about 40 miles (64 km) of surface streets, the route travels along I-280 for the final 1.5 miles (2.4 km) of that freeway, exiting near Mission Bay and Oracle Park.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] It winds along The Embarcadero and underneath the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge—once the final leg of the route before its Treasure Island terminus.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] At Market Street, the route crosses in front of the Ferry Building and shortly thereafter turns westward along Washington Street to enter the Financial District.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Proceeding south on the often-congested Battery Street, the route crosses Market Street and enters the SoMA neighborhood on 1st Street.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Turning again at Howard Street, the route passes the SFMOMA, Yerba Buena Gardens, and Moscone Center before making its final turn onto 9th Street, crossing Market once more, and returning to Civic Center Plaza.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route ends where it began, in front of City Hall, after traveling 46.3 miles (74.5 km).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] In the late 1930s, residents of San Francisco and the greater Bay Area celebrated the completion of both the Golden Gate Bridge and San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Roosevelt was given a vehicular tour of the city, including its two bridges, with Senator William Gibbs McAdoo and Mayor Angelo Joseph Rossi before speaking at the Treasure Island fairgrounds, site of the Golden Gate International Exposition of 1939–40.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Later that year, the San Francisco Down Town Association devised a route from behind City Hall to Treasure Island that was originally titled the "50-Mile Scenic Drive", marking the way with blue and gold triangular signs.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The name was changed shortly thereafter—probably with marketing intentions—to reflect San Francisco's approximate area (46.9 square miles (121 km2)) and reference the California Gold Rush of 1849, from which the term "forty-niner" originates.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The Down Town Association produced brochures highlighting the scenic drive for tourists.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] On September 14, 1938, the 49-Mile Scenic Drive was officially opened by Douglas Corrigan, who had achieved fame (and his nickname, "Wrong Way") earlier in 1938 for claiming to fly from New York City to Los Angeles but ending up in Dublin.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Corrigan drove at least part of the route in reverse on that day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] After the Golden Gate International Exposition was closed in 1940, control of Treasure Island was transferred to the U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Navy, and the drive was rerouted for the first time.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] During World War II, civilian access to the Presidio was closed, the route effectively closing along with it.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 1947, the drive reopened with an expanded southeastern segment, which now continued south past Mission San Francisco de Asís to Excelsior, McLaren Park, and Visitacion Valley before returning via the Bayshore Freeway and Bryant Street to The Embarcadero.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 1954, the Down Town Association held a contest to design a new sign to mark the route, offering the winner a $100 prize.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Local artist Rex May submitted the winning entry, a seagull in profile on a sky blue background with white and orange text.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The signs have proved a popular target for theft and many portions of the route are unsigned.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The San Francisco Department of Parking and Traffic, which manages the signs, attempts to replace them when they are informed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] By 1976, the drive had been rerouted once more.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The initial segment now moved west from Van Ness Avenue through Japantown, showcasing the recently completed Japan Center.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] A more complex loop through Chinatown included a trip up Nob Hill.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] A formalized detour to Fort Point was indicated, and the route now turned in Lincoln Park to reach Cliff House via Geary Boulevard instead of Fort Miley.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] A longer route through Golden Gate Park now included a circle of Stow Lake from the north, and the southeastern loop to Visitacion Valley was truncated and replaced by a turn on Army Street (Cesar Chavez).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Finally, a new segment on Interstate 280 allowed the drive to return to The Embarcadero.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Changes included beginning at Civic Center Plaza rather than on Van Ness Avenue, removing the former detour to Coit Tower, and traveling on Howard Street instead of Market Street at the end of the route.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Kennedy Drive in Golden Gate Park was closed to vehicular traffic.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 2022, the San Francisco Board of Supervisors voted to permanently keep the 1.5-mile stretch of JFK Drive closed to vehicles, making it a permanent car-free route known as the JFK Promenade.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] On March 14, 2025, a two-mile stretch of Great Highway along the Pacific Ocean was closed to traffic permanently.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] With the road closures in 2020 and 2025, and with no alternative routes either planned or proposed by the San Francisco Department of Public Works, the agency unofficially but effectively decommissioned the Scenic Drive.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The 49-Mile Scenic Route is a modern reimagining of San Francisco's historic 49-Mile Scenic Drive, designed to offer a walkable, bikeable, and transit-friendly exploration of the city's diverse neighborhoods and landmarks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Initiated by San Francisco Chronicle reporters Heather Knight and Peter Hartlaub in 2019, this updated route emphasizes accessibility and inclusivity, moving away from the car-centric approach of the original drive.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] It is a scenic tour of San Francisco designed to be accessible to non-drivers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] It is an alternative to the 49-Mile Scenic Drive.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] In 2019, Peter Hartlaub and Heather Knight of the *San Francisco Chronicle* wrote a series of articles about a proposed new scenic route.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] They started by doing the existing scenic drive via a variety of non-car modes of transport to figure out what works when not driving.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] After publishing their initial experience, *Chronicle* readers were invited to take a survey about the proposed scenic route.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route measures just over 49 miles, and adds neighborhoods such as Ingleside, The Bayview, and Bernal Heights, as well as multiple parks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The scenic route also highlights independent bookstores, neighborhood theaters, museums, art galleries, and restaurants.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] While the scenic drive started at City Hall, the scenic route starts at the San Francisco Chronicle building at 5th and Mission.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] Like the drive, the route proceeds counterclockwise around the city.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The section from the Financial District to the entrance of the Presidio is the same on both the scenic route and the scenic drive.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/49-mile-scenic-drive] The route leaves off some parts of the Richmond District and Sea Cliff.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The park is bordered by Hayes Street to the south, Steiner Street to the east, Fulton Street to the north, and Scott Street to the west.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] Named after the lone cottonwood tree ("álamo" in Spanish), Alamo Hill, was a watering hole on the horseback trail from Mission Dolores to the Presidio in the 1800s.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] In 1856, Mayor James Van Ness created a 12.7 acres (5.1 ha) park surrounding the watering hole, creating "Alamo Square".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] Alamo Square Park is a 13.6-acre (5.5 ha) public park located in the neighborhood.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] Open daily from 5am to midnight, it is owned and operated by the San Francisco Recreation & Parks Department.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] It includes a playground and a tennis court, and is frequented by neighbors, tourists, and dog owners.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] On a clear day, the Transamerica Pyramid building and the tops of the Golden Gate Bridge and Bay Bridge can be seen from the park's center.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The San Francisco City Hall can be seen directly down Fulton Street.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The area is part of the city's fifth Supervisorial district and is served by several Muni bus lines, including the 5, 21, 22, and 24.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] In 2016 it was closed for a $4.3 million renovation lasting seven months.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The Alamo Square neighborhood is characterized by Victorian architecture that was left largely untouched by the urban renewal projects in other parts of the Western Addition.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The Alamo Square area contains the second largest concentration of homes over 10,000 square feet (930 m2) in San Francisco, after the Pacific Heights neighborhood.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] A row of Victorian houses facing the park on Steiner Street, known as the "Painted Ladies", are often shown in the foreground of panoramic pictures of the city's downtown area.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] A number of movies, television shows and commercials have been filmed in or around Alamo Square.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The park features heavily in the 1978 horror film *The Invasion of the Body Snatchers*, and the 2012 romantic comedy *The Five-Year Engagement*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The opening sequence of the American sitcom *Full House* (1987–1995) features a romp in Alamo Square Park with the famous row of Victorians in the background.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] There are many architecturally significant mansions on the perimeter of the park, including the William Westerfeld House, the Archbishop's Mansion, the residences of the Russian and German Imperial consuls in the early 1900s, and the mansions on the block diagonally across from the Painted Ladies.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] The demographics of the neighborhood are characteristic of other urban neighborhoods that have undergone gentrification: many young people and upper-middle-class homeowners, in addition to a diverse older population.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] Efforts on the part of Alamo Square and North Panhandle residents and merchants have led to restrictions on chain stores on the corridor.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] Neighborhood groups include the Alamo Square Neighborhood Association and the Haight-Divisadero Neighborhood Merchants Association.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alamo-square-san-francisco] Author Alice Walker lived in one of the "Painted Lady" Victorians across from Alamo Square park up to the mid-1990s.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz Island has the oldest operating lighthouse on the West Coast of the United States, early military fortifications, and natural features such as rock pools and a seabird colony (mostly western gulls, cormorants, and egrets).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] According to a 1971 documentary on the history of Alcatraz, the island measures 1,675 feet (511 m) by 590 feet (180 m) and is 135 feet (41 m) at highest point during mean tide.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The total area of the island is reported to be 22 acres (8.9 ha).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1972, Alcatraz was transferred to the Department of Interior to become part of Golden Gate National Recreation Area.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The island's facilities are managed by the National Park Service.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] It was designated as a National Historic Landmark in 1986.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Hornblower Cruises, operating under the name Alcatraz City Cruises, is the official ferry provider at Pier 33, located between the San Francisco Ferry Building and Fisherman's Wharf.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Landmarks on the island include the Main Cellhouse, Dining Hall, Lighthouse, the ruins of the Warden's House and Social Hall, Parade Grounds, Building 64, Water Tower, New Industries Building, Model Industries Building, and the Recreation Yard.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The first European to document the islands of San Francisco Bay was Spanish naval officer and explorer Juan Manuel de Ayala during the Spanish rule of California; he charted San Francisco Bay in 1775.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] He named today's Yerba Buena Island as *"La Isla de los Alcatraces"*, which translates as "The Island of the Gannets", but is commonly believed to translate as "The Island of the Pelicans" (the modern Spanish word for pelican is *pelícano*), from the archaic Spanish **alcatraz** ("pelican").
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] No gannets are native to the Pacific Coast, making the older Spanish usage more likely.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Yerba Buena Island was labeled on Ayala's 1775 chart of San Francisco Bay as "Isla de Alcatraces".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The name was later applied to the rock now known as Alcatraz Island by Captain Frederick W.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Beechey, an English naval officer and explorer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Over the years, the Spanish version "Alcatraz" became popular and is now widely used.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In August 1827, for instance, French Captain Auguste Bernard Duhaut-Cilly wrote "... running past Alcatraze's (Pelicans) Island ... covered with a countless number of these birds.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] A gun fired over the feathered legions caused them to fly up in a great cloud and with a noise like a hurricane." The California brown pelican (*Pelecanus occidentalis californicus*) is not known to nest on the island today.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The Spanish built several small buildings on the island and other minor structures.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The earliest recorded private owner of the island of Alcatraz is Julian Workman, to whom it was given by Mexican Governor Pio Pico in June 1846, with the understanding that Workman would build a lighthouse on it.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Julian Workman is the baptismal name of William Workman, co-owner of Rancho La Puente and a personal friend of Pio Pico.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Later in 1846, acting in his capacity as military governor of California, John C.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Frémont bought the island for $5,000 in the name of the United States government from Francis Temple.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1850, President Millard Fillmore ordered that Alcatraz Island be set aside specifically as a United States military reservation, for military purposes based upon the U.S. acquisition of California from Mexico following the Mexican–American War.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Frémont had expected a large compensation for his initiative in purchasing and securing Alcatraz Island for the U.S. government, but the U.S. government later invalidated the sale and paid Frémont nothing.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Frémont and his heirs sued for compensation during protracted but unsuccessful legal battles that extended into the 1890s.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Following the acquisition of California by the United States as a result of the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo (1848), which ended the Mexican–American War, and the onset of the California Gold Rush the following year, the U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Army began studying the suitability of Alcatraz Island for the positioning of coastal batteries to protect the approaches to San Francisco Bay.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1853, under the direction of Zealous B.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Tower, the United States Army Corps of Engineers began fortifying the island, work which continued until 1858, when the initial version of Fort Alcatraz was complete.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The island's first garrison, numbering about 200 soldiers, arrived at the end of that year.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] When the American Civil War broke out in 1861, the island mounted 85 cannons (increased to 105 cannons by 1866) in casements around its perimeter, though the small size of the garrison meant only a fraction of the guns could be used at one time.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] At this time, it also served as the San Francisco Arsenal for storage of firearms to prevent them falling into the hands of Confederate sympathizers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz, built as a "heavily fortified military site on the West Coast", was to form a "triangle of defense" with Fort Point and Lime Point, but the contemplated work on Lime Point was never built.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The first operational lighthouse on the West Coast of the United States was also built on Alcatraz.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] During the war, Fort Alcatraz was used to imprison Confederate sympathizers and privateers on the west coast, but its guns were never fired at an enemy.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Studies of the island and its fortifications have included archeological surveys relying on contemporary technology.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Archaeologists also found the remains of ammunition magazines, and tunnels below the penitentiary that was built later.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Because of the isolation created by the cold, strong currents of the waters of San Francisco Bay, as early as 1859, Alcatraz was used to house soldiers convicted of crimes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] By 1861, the fort was the military prison for the Department of the Pacific.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] It housed Civil War prisoners of war (POWs) as early as that year.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Starting in 1863, the military also held private citizens accused of treason, after the writ of habeas corpus in the United States was suspended.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Hundreds of troops were trained on the island, with more than 350 military personnel in place by April 1861.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] As enlistees were assigned to units, new green troops reported for training.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In early 1865, the number of men reached 433, the peak of the war.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] During the Civil War-era, rapid changes in artillery and fortification were generated.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz's defenses were obsolete by the postwar years.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Instead, the army switched the focus of its plans for Alcatraz from coastal defense to detention, a task for which it was well suited because of its isolation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1867, a brick jailhouse was built (previously inmates had been kept in the basement of the guardhouse), and in 1868, Alcatraz was officially designated as a long-term detention facility for military prisoners.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The facility was later discontinued for Prisoners of War in 1846.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Among those incarcerated at Alcatraz were Confederates caught on the West Coast and some Hopi Native American men in the 1870s, who refused orders to send their children away from their families to Indian boarding schools.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1898, due to the Spanish–American War, the prison population rose from 26 to over 450.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] From 1905 to 1907 it was commanded by U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] After the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, civilian prisoners were transferred to Alcatraz for safe confinement.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] On March 21, 1907, Alcatraz was officially designated as the Western U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Military Prison, later Pacific Branch, U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1909 construction began on the huge concrete main cell block, designed by Major Reuben Turner, which remains the island's dominant feature.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] To accommodate the new cell block, the Citadel, a three-story barracks, was demolished down to the first floor, which was below ground level.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The building had been constructed in an excavated pit, creating a defensive dry moat.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The first floor was incorporated as a basement to the new cell block, giving rise to the popular legend of "dungeons" below the main cell block.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The US Disciplinary Barracks was deactivated in October 1933 and transferred to the Bureau of Prisons.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] During World War I, the prison was used to hold conscientious objectors, including Philip Grosser, who wrote a pamphlet entitled *Uncle Sam's Devil's Island* about his experiences.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The United States Disciplinary Barracks on Alcatraz were acquired by the United States Department of Justice on October 12, 1933, and the island was designated as a federal prison in August 1934.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz was designed to hold prisoners who continuously caused trouble at other federal prisons.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] At 9:40 am on August 11, 1934, the first batch of 137 prisoners arrived at Alcatraz, arriving by railroad from the United States Penitentiary in Leavenworth, Kansas, to Santa Venetia, California.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] They were escorted to Alcatraz, while handcuffed in high security coaches and guarded by 60 special FBI agents, U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Marshals and railway security officials.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Most of the prisoners were notorious bank robbers and murderers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The prison initially had a staff of 155, including the first warden James A.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Shuttleworth, both considered to be "iron men".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The staff were highly trained in security, but not rehabilitation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Despite what was said about the jail, prisoners requested to be transferred to Alcatraz Island due to its single-cell occupancy and high quality of food.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] "Doc" Barker, and Alvin "Creepy" Karpis, who served more time at Alcatraz than any other inmate.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz Island also served as a residential community for Bureau of Prisons staff and their families.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Correctional officers and their families lived in designated apartment buildings on the island.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Contrary to popular belief, it was possible to escape and swim all of the way to shore.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] During its 29 years of operation, the penitentiary claimed that no prisoner successfully escaped.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] A total of 36 prisoners made 14 escape attempts, two men trying twice.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] 23 were caught alive, six were shot and killed during their escape, two drowned, and five are listed as "missing and presumed drowned".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The most violent incident occurred on May 2, 1946, when a failed escape attempt by six prisoners led to the Battle of Alcatraz.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Perhaps the most famous is the intricate escape, carried out on June 11, 1962, by Frank Morris, John Anglin, and Clarence Anglin.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The three men are believed to have drowned in their attempt.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] No bodies were ever found, sparking speculation that they made it to shore and escaped.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] On June 11, 1962, brothers John and Clarence Anglin and Frank Morris escaped Alcatraz prison.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] John, Clarence, and Frank were all doing time for committing crimes such as bank robbery.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] They did this by digging through a vent for approximately three months, once they reached the top it took additional time to file down the bolts of the roof vents.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] They used sharpened spoons, a vacuum cleaner motor drill, and any other tools they could find to make the hole in the vent bigger and get through the bolted roof top vent.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] To fulfill their plan of escaping they made realistic dummy heads by using papier-mâché to disguise them while the guards did nightly checks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] They used hair clippings to make it believable that they were still sleeping in their beds during nightly checks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Getting out of the prison was only half their plan: they had to make it 1.25 miles to shore in shark infested waters.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] They created rafts out of prison rain jackets and several life preservers; they were able to contract this idea from magazines they had read while in prison.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] They came up with a waterproof glue as well to keep the raft together in the water.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Then they made wooden paddles out of leftover wood scraps and plywood found around the prison.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] To inflate their raft, they stole a concertina.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] At around 10pm on June 11th 1962 they made the escape and were never seen again.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] A fourth prisoner, Allen West, had intended to escape with Morris and the Anglins, but failed to get out of his cell in time.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] He later cooperated with the FBI during their investigation, revealing the finer details of the escape plan.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Although most escapees were caught or drowned, in 1962, prisoner John Paul Scott made it to the shore.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] He was so weary that police found him unconscious and in hypothermic shock.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The annual Escape from Alcatraz Triathlon includes a required 1.5-mile (2.4 km) swim from the island to the bay shore.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] There are several reasons that Alcatraz closed as a penitentiary in 1963.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The penitentiary cost much more to operate than other prisons (nearly $10 per prisoner per day, as opposed to $3 per prisoner per day at Atlanta).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Additionally, there was no source of fresh water on the island; nearly one million gallons per week had to be transported from the mainland.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Half a century of salt water saturation had severely eroded the buildings and three prisoners had purportedly escaped in 1962.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In the years after its closure, the San Francisco mayor's office received various public proposals to repurpose Alcatraz Island.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz Island was occupied by Native American activists for the first time on March 8, 1964.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The protest, proposed by Lakota Sioux activist Belva Cottier and joined by about 35 others, was reported by, among others, the *San Francisco Chronicle* and the *San Francisco Examiner*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Beginning on November 20, 1969, a group of Native Americans called United Indians of All Tribes, mostly college students from San Francisco, occupied the island to protest federal policies related to American Indians.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Some of them were children of Native Americans who had relocated in the city as part of the Bureau of Indian Affairs' (BIA) Indian termination policy, which was a series of laws and policies aimed at the assimilation of Native Americans into mainstream US society.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] It encouraged Native Americans to move away from the Indian reservations and into cities to take advantage of health, educational and employment opportunities.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] A number of employees of the Bureau of Indian Affairs also occupied Alcatraz at that time, including Doris Purdy, an amateur photographer, who later produced footage of her stay on the island.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The occupiers, who stayed on the island for nearly two years, demanded that the island's facilities be adapted and new structures built for an Indian education center, ecology center, and cultural center.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The American Indians claimed the island by provisions of the Treaty of Fort Laramie (1868) between the US and the Sioux; they said the treaty promised to return all retired, abandoned, or out-of-use federal lands to the native peoples from whom they were acquired.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Indians of All Tribes claimed Alcatraz Island by the "Right of Discovery"; as historian Troy R.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Johnson states in *The Occupation of Alcatraz Island*, generations of indigenous peoples knew about Alcatraz at least 10,000 years before any European knew about any part of North America.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Begun by urban Indians of San Francisco, the occupation attracted other Native Americans from across the country, including American Indian Movement (AIM) urban activists from Minneapolis.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] During the nineteen months and nine days of occupation by the American Indians, several buildings at Alcatraz were damaged or destroyed by fire, including the lighthouse keeper's home, the warden's home, the Officers' Club, the recreation hall, and the Coast Guard quarters.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The US government demolished a number of other buildings (mostly apartments) after the occupation had ended.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Graffiti from the period of Native American occupation is still visible at many locations on the island.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] During the occupation, President Richard Nixon rescinded the Indian termination policy, designed by earlier administrations to end federal recognition of many tribes and their special relationship with the US government.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] He established a new policy of self-determination, in part as a result of the publicity and awareness created by the occupation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1972, the National Park Service purchased Alcatraz along with Fort Mason from the U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Army to establish the Golden Gate National Recreation Area.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Under "An Act to Establish the Golden Gate National Recreation Area" President Richard Nixon allocated $120 million for land acquisition and development of the area.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] It operates as a tourist site and museum dedicated to its time as a federal penitentiary.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Operating costs still remain one of its biggest challenges.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] On May 4, 2025, President Donald Trump proposed reopening the island's prison.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The White House budget in 2026 requested $152 million to reopen the prison as a secure facility.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Part of the Golden Gate National Recreation Area since 1972, the entire Alcatraz Island was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1976.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1986 it was designated as a National Historic Landmark, the highest recognition.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 1993, the National Park Service published a plan entitled *Alcatraz Development Concept and Environmental Assessment.* This plan, approved in 1980, doubled the area of Alcatraz accessible to the public, in order to enable visitors to enjoy its scenery and bird, marine, and animal life.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] American Indigenous groups, such as the International Indian Treaty Council, occasionally hold ceremonies on the island, most notably, their "Sunrise Gatherings" every Columbus Day and Thanksgiving Day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Around 2007, the Global Peace Foundation proposed to raze the prison and build a peace center in its place.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Supporters collected 10,350 signatures – sufficient to have it placed as a proposition on the presidential primary ballots in San Francisco for February 5, 2008.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The proposed plan was estimated at US$1 billion.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] For the plan to pass, Congress would have to have taken Alcatraz out of the National Park Service.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Critics of the plan said that Alcatraz is too rich in history to be destroyed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] On February 6, 2008, the Alcatraz Island Global Peace Center Proposition C failed to pass, with 72% of voters rejecting the proposition.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The coastal environment of the San Francisco Bay Area has caused deterioration and corrosion of building materials throughout Alcatraz.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Beginning in 2011, the National Park Service began major renovations on the island, including the installation of solar panels on the cell house roof, slope stabilization near the Warden's House, and the stabilization and rehabilitation of the outer cell house walls.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Now one of San Francisco's major tourist attractions, Alcatraz drew some 1.7 million visitors annually according to a 2018 report.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Visitors arrive by ferry, operated under contract by Alcatraz Cruises LLC at Pier 33.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The 2018 report indicated that "former prison buildings are being conserved and seismically upgraded and additional areas of the Island are opened to the public as safety hazards are removed".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] During the COVID-19 pandemic, the buildings and the island remained closed to the public for more than a year (and ferry services were suspended), reopening in March 2021.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz has been home to several art installations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 2014, Chinese artist/dissident Ai Weiwei staged an exhibition which explored "questions about human rights and freedom of expression" called @Large.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] This exhibition included Lego portraits of famous political prisoners.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The creation of the exhibition was featured in a 2019 documentary film, *Ai Weiwei: Yours Truly*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In 2016, Nelson Saiers used math and prison slang as central elements in a six-month installation that called attention to the imposition of long prison sentences.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Gardens planted by families of the original Army post, and later by families of the prison guards, fell into neglect after the prison closure in 1963.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] After 40 years, they are being restored by a paid staff member and many volunteers, thanks to funding by the Garden Conservancy and the Golden Gate National Parks Conservancy.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] The untended gardens had become severely overgrown and had developed into a nesting habitat and sanctuary for numerous birds.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Now, areas of bird habitat are being preserved and protected, while many of the gardens are being restored to their original state.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] In clearing out the overgrowth, workers found that many of the original plants were growing where they had been planted – some more than 100 years ago.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Numerous heirloom rose hybrids, including a Welsh rose (Bardou Job) that had been believed to be extinct, have been discovered and propagated.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Many species of roses, succulents, and geraniums are growing among apple and fig trees, banks of sweet peas, manicured gardens of cutting flowers, and wildly overgrown sections of native grasses with blackberry and honeysuckle.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Abrams' 2012 television series *Alcatraz*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] It also was featured in the anime *Yu-Gi-Oh!
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Duel Monsters*, the book *Al Capone Does My Shirts* and the video game *Tony Hawk's Pro Skater 4* as a playable level.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] It is also showcased as a playable racetrack in the 1997 arcade racing video game *San Francisco Rush the Rock: Alcatraz Edition*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcatraz-island] Alcatraz has also been portrayed often as a safe haven or base of operations in many post-apocalyptic movies, such as *The Book of Eli*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] France, alcohol by volume is often referred to as **degrees Gay-Lussac** (after the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac), although there is a slight difference since the Gay-Lussac convention uses the International Standard Atmosphere value for temperature, 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing two solutions of alcohol of different strengths usually causes a change in volume.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Mixing pure water with a solution less than 24% by mass causes a slight increase in total volume, whereas the mixing of two solutions above 24% causes a decrease in volume.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The phenomenon of volume changes due to mixing dissimilar solutions is called "partial molar volume".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Water and ethanol are both polar solvents.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] When water is added to ethanol, the smaller water molecules are attracted to the ethanol's hydroxyl group, and each molecule alters the polarity field of the other.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The attraction allows closer spacing between molecules than is usually found in non-polar mixtures.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Thus, alc/vol is not the same as volume fraction expressed as a percentage.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Volume fraction, which is widely used in chemistry (commonly denoted as v/v), is defined as the volume of a particular component divided by the sum of all components in the mixture when they are measured separately.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] For example, to make 100 mL of 50% alc/vol ethanol solution, water would be added to 50 mL of ethanol to make up exactly 100 mL.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Whereas to make a 50% v/v ethanol solution, 50 mL of ethanol and 50 mL of water could be mixed but the resulting volume of solution will measure less than 100 mL due to the change of volume on mixing, and will contain a higher concentration of ethanol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The difference is not large, with the maximum difference being less than 2.5%, and less than 0.5% difference for concentrations under 20%.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Some drinks have requirements of alcoholic content in order to be certified as a certain alcohol brand or label.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] For example, in the United Kingdom, the United States, Canada and European Union whisky is legally required to be no less than 40% ABV bottled.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Low-alcohol beers (<0.5) are considered in some countries such as Iran as permitted (halal) despite alcohol being banned.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] However, the level of alcohol-free beers is typically the lowest commercially sold 0.05.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] It is near impossible for a healthy person to become intoxicated drinking low-alcohol drinks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The low concentration severely limits the rate of intake, which is easily dispatched by human metabolism.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Quickly drinking 1.5 L of 0.4% alc/vol beer in an hour resulted in a maximum of 0.0056% BAC in a study of German volunteers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Healthy human kidneys can only excrete 0.8–1.0 L of water per hour, making water intoxication likely to set in before any alcoholic intoxication.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The process of ethanol fermentation will slow down and eventually come to a halt as the alcohol produced becomes too concentrated for the yeast to tolerate, defining an upper limit of alc/vol for non-distilled alcoholic drinks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The typical tolerance for beer yeasts is at 8–12%, while wine yeasts typically range from 14–18%, with speciality ones reaching 20% alc/vol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Any higher would require distillation, producing liquor.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Details about typical amounts of alcohol contained in various beverages can be found in the articles about them.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] During the production of wine and beer, yeast is added to a sugary solution.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] During fermentation, the yeasts consume the sugars and produce alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The density of sugar in water is greater than the density of alcohol in water.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] A hydrometer is used to measure the change in specific gravity (SG) of the solution before and after fermentation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The volume of alcohol in the solution can then be estimated.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] There are a number of empirical formulae which brewers and winemakers use to estimate the alcohol content of the liquor made.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Specific gravity is the density of a liquid relative to that of water, i.e., if the density of the liquid is 1.05 times that of water, it has a specific gravity of 1.05.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] In UK brewing usage, it is customary to regard the reference value for water to be 1000, so the specific gravity of the same example beer would be quoted as 1050.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The formulas here assume that the former definition is used for specific gravity.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] During ethanol fermentation the yeast converts one mole of sugar into two moles of alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] where 46.069 is the molar mass of ethanol and 180.156 is the molar mass of glucose and fructose.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] SG can be measured using an hydrometer and Brix can be calculated from SG.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] SG drop is how much the SG decreased during fermentation (at 20 degree C).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The factor 135 is most accurate in the center of the SG drop range of 0.000 to 0.179.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Advanced formula derived from Carl Balling empirical formulas.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The formula compensates for changes in SG with changes in alcohol concentration and for the fact that not all sugar is converted into alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] where SG final is the specific gravity when fermentation ends, Plato start is the sugar by weight when fermentation begins, Plato final is the sugar by weight when fermentation ends.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Brix can be used instead of Plato as they are nearly identical.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Another way of specifying the amount of alcohol content is alcohol *proof*, which in the United States is twice the alcohol-by-volume (alc/vol) number.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] This may lead to confusion over similar products bought in varying regions that have different names on country-specific labels.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] For example, Stroh rum that is 80% ABV is advertised and labeled as *Stroh 80* when sold in Europe, but is named *Stroh 160* when sold in the United States.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] In the United Kingdom, proof is 1.75 times the number (expressed as a percentage).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] For example, 40% alc/vol is 80 proof in the US and 70 proof in the UK.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] However, since 1980, alcohol proof in the UK has been replaced by alc/vol as a measure of alcohol content, avoiding confusion between the UK and US proof standards.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] In the United States, Arkansas, Kansas, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Tennessee regulate and tax alcoholic beverages according to **alcohol by weight** (**ABW**), expressed as a percentage of total mass.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] The alc/vol value of a beverage is always higher than the ABW.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] Because ABW measures the proportion of the drink's mass which is alcohol, while alc/vol is the proportion of the drink's volume which is alcohol, the two values are in the same proportion as the drink's density is with the density of alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] At relatively low alc/vol, the alcohol percentage by weight is about 4/5 of the alc/vol (e.g., 3.2% ABW is about 4% alc/vol).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcohol-by-volume] However, because of the miscibility of alcohol and water, the conversion factor is not constant but rather depends upon the concentration of alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] An **alcoholic beverage** (also called an **alcoholic drink** or **strong drink**) is any drink that contains alcohol, a central nervous system depressant.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] They are typically divided into three classes: beers, wines, and spirits; with alcohol content typically between 3% and 50%.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The exact amount on which a beverage is considered alcoholic differs by country, with some considering drinks containing less than 0.5% to be non-alcoholic.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] These beverages are primarily consumed for the psychoactive effects that they produce.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Many societies have a distinct drinking culture, in which alcoholic drinks are integrated into parties.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws regulating the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some regulations require the labeling of the percentage alcohol content (as ABV or proof) and the use of a warning label.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries ban the consumption of alcoholic drinks, but they are legal in most parts of the world.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The temperance movement advocates against the consumption of alcoholic beverages.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The global alcoholic drink industry exceeded $1.5 trillion in 2017.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is one of the most widely used recreational drugs in the world, and about 33% of all humans currently drink alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In 2015, among Americans, 86% of adults had consumed alcohol at some point, with 70% drinking it in the last year and 56% in the last month.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Several other animals are affected by alcohol similarly to humans and, once they consume it, will consume it again if given the opportunity; however, humans are the only species known to produce alcoholic drinks intentionally.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, a class of psychoactive drug that slows down activity in the central nervous system.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In low doses it causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death (an overdose).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to alcoholism, an increased risk of developing several types of cancer, cardiovascular disease, and physical dependence.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is classified as a group 1 carcinogen.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Discovery of late Stone Age jugs suggests that intentionally fermented drinks existed at least as early as the Neolithic period.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The oldest verifiable brewery has been found in a prehistoric burial site in a cave near Haifa in modern-day Israel.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Researchers have found residue of 13,000-year-old beer that they think might have been used for ritual feasts to honor the dead.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The traces of a wheat-and-barley-based alcohol were found in stone mortars carved into the cave floor.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The Carmona Wine Urn is a first century Roman glass urn containing intact wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was likely brewed from barley as early as 13,000 years ago in the Middle East.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Pliny the Elder wrote about the *golden age* of winemaking in Rome, the 2nd century BCE (200–100 BCE), when vineyards were planted.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Examination and analysis of ancient pottery jars from the neolithic village of Jiahu in the Henan province of northern China revealed residue left behind by the alcoholic drinks they had once contained.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Chemical analysis of the residue confirmed that a fermented drink made of grape and hawthorn fruit wine, honey mead and rice beer was being produced in 7000–5600 BC.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The residence in which the jar was discovered and other houses in the same village were found to contain many such jars suggesting that wine was an important part of their diet.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest evidence of winemaking was dated at 6,000 to 5,800 BCE in Georgia in the South Caucasus.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Excavations surrounding Neolithic settlements there unearthed grape pips of a variety which differed from those of wild grapes, pointing to deliberate cultivation, and local pottery dated to approximately 6000 BCE was decorated with depictions of celebrating human figures.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The earliest clear chemical evidence of beer produced from barley dates to about 3500–3100 BCE, from the site of Godin Tepe in the Zagros Mountains of western Iran.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] At a site dating to 3100-2900 BCE, a pottery vessel containing residue of alcoholic barley was discovered, possibly serving as the earliest proof of beer brewing in the region.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] However, it is unclear whether it was meant for intoxication or nourishment.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Celtic people were known to have been making types of alcoholic cider as early as 3000 BCE. and wine was consumed in Classical Greece at breakfast or at symposia, and in the 1st century BCE.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological finds as well as ancient documentation serve as testimony to the popularity and abundance of alcohol in the Sumerian society.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Access to alcohol was regulated, the social elite indulged in it and it served as sacrificial offerings to the gods.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In Sumerian culture Alcohol was also a means for happiness.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In the epic of Gilgamesh, Enkidu the wild man drinks seven jugs of beer, becomes elated and sings with joy.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Other characters routinely drink water, but drink alcohol when celebrating.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] During the new year celebrations, the ceremonial reenactment of the drunken union between the king of Uruk and the high priestess of Ishtar, the goddess of procreation, symbolized the genesis of Ninkasi, the beer goddess.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A hymn to Ninkasi gives a detailed description of hash production in Sumer, involving the fermentation of bread and the addition of grapes and honey, resulting in an unfiltered brew drunk through straws.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In Hierakonpolis, Egypt, the remains of a brewery dating to circa 3400 BCE was unearthed, with an estimated yield of up to 1135 litres (300 US gallons) of brew per day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine was a symbol of power and was imported from abroad, hence it was reserved for royalty and the social elite, while beer was the drink of common society.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In the tomb of the Scorpion king, who ruled Hierakonpolis when the brewery was built, approximately 700 wine jars imported from the southern Levant were unearthed.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Financial documents recorded that the daily ration of beer for the workers who built the pyramids of Giza was nearly 4 litres, and modern reproductions of the ancient recipe produced a brew weighed in at 5 percent ABV, the same as that of the modern day pint.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Despite the many Egyptian sources describing brewing methods, very few discuss intoxication.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In honor of this deed a red coloured alcohol was drunk in large quantities during the festival causing similar intoxicated stupors.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Osiris was also associated with wine, as his death and resurrection were compared to the cycle of withering and regrowth of the vine during the winter and spring.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Multiple amphorae were discovered in the graves of pharaohs and elites as provisions for the afterlife and as offerings to Osiris, commonly with labels detailing their origin, maker, and date.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Over time, labels eventually included assessments of quality as well, such as "good," (*nfr*) "very good," (*nfr nfr*) or "very very good," (*nfr nfr nfr*) alongside provenance, and it was believed that certain vintages improved with age.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Archaeological findings reveal that some wines buried with their owners were several decades old, exceeding the average life expectancy, and therefore assumed to have outlived their creators.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Medieval Muslim chemists such as Jābir ibn Ḥayyān (Latin: Geber, ninth century) and Abū Bakr al-Rāzī (Latin: Rhazes, c.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] 865–925) experimented extensively with the distillation of various substances.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The distillation of wine is attested in Arabic works attributed to al-Kindī (c.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] 872–950), and in the 28th book of al-Zahrāwī's (Latin: Abulcasis, 936–1013) *Kitāb al-Taṣrīf* (later translated into Latin as *Liber servatoris*).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] 12th century: The process of distillation spread from the Middle East to Italy, where distilled alcoholic drinks were recorded in the mid-12th century.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In Italy, the works of Taddeo Alderotti (1223–1296) describe a method for concentrating alcohol involving repeated fractional distillation through a water-cooled still.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] By the early 14th century, distilled alcoholic drinks had spread throughout the European continent.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Distillation spread to Ireland and Scotland no later than the 15th century, as did the common European practice of distilling "aqua vitae", primarily for medicinal purposes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking hard liquor was common occurrence in early nineteenth-century United States.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The Whiskey Rebellion (also known as the Whiskey Insurrection) was a violent tax protest in the United States beginning in 1791 and ending in 1794 during the presidency of George Washington.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The so-called "whiskey tax" was the first tax imposed on a domestic product by the newly formed federal government.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Beer was difficult to transport and spoiled more easily than rum and whiskey.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The Rum Rebellion of 1808 was a *coup d'état* in the then-British penal colony of New South Wales, staged by the New South Wales Corps in order to depose Governor William Bligh.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Australia's first and only military coup, its name derives from the illicit rum trade of early Sydney, over which the 'Rum Corps', as it became known, maintained a monopoly.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] During the first half of the 19th century, it was widely referred to in Australia as the Great Rebellion.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly system has a long history in various countries, often implemented to limit the availability and consumption of alcohol for public health and social welfare reasons.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The alcohol monopoly was created in the Swedish town of Falun in 1850, to prevent overconsumption and reduce the profit motive for sales of alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It later went all over the country in 1905 when the Swedish parliament ordered all sales of vodka to be done via local alcohol monopolies.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In 1894, the Russian Empire established a state monopoly on vodka, which became a major source of revenue for the Russian government.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is a beverage fermented from grain mash.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It is typically made from barley or a blend of several grains and flavored with hops.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Most beer is naturally carbonated as part of the fermentation process.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] If the fermented mash is distilled, then the drink becomes a spirit.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Beer is the most consumed alcoholic beverage in the world.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Cider or cyder (/ˈsaɪdər/ *SY-dər*) is a fermented alcoholic drink made from any fruit juice; apple juice (traditional and most common), peaches, pears ("Perry" cider) or other fruit.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Cider alcohol content varies from 1.2% ABV to 8.5% or more in traditional English ciders.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In some regions, cider may be called "apple wine".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is an ethanol-based water solution with approximately 15-17% ABV without sweet reserve.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is exclusively fermented with white sugar, yeast, and water.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fermented water is clarified after the fermentation to produce a colorless or off-white liquid with no discernible taste other than that of ethanol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Mead (/miːd/), also called hydromel, is an alcoholic drink made by fermenting honey with water, sometimes with various fruits, spices, grains, or hops.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The alcoholic content of mead may range from as low as 3% ABV to more than 20%.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The defining characteristic of mead is that the majority of the drink's fermentable sugar is derived from honey.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque is the Mesoamerican fermented drink made from the "honey water" of maguey, *Agave americana*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Pulque can be distilled to produce tequila or Mezcal.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Rice wine is an alcoholic drink fermented and possibly distilled from rice, consumed in East Asia, Southeast Asia and South Asia.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Sake, huangjiu, mijiu, and cheongju are popular examples of East Asian rice wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is a fermented beverage most commonly produced from grapes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine involves a longer fermentation process than beer and often a long aging process (months or years), resulting in an alcohol content of 9%–16% ABV.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Sparkling wines such as French Champagne, Catalan Cava and Italian Prosecco are also made from grapes, with a secondary fermentation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fruit wines are made from fruits other than grapes, such as plums, cherries, or apples.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine, beer, and spirits are produced through the activity of yeasts, a group of roughly 160 species of single-celled fungi, some of which are beneficial, while others are associated with food spoilage or human disease.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The most commonly used yeasts in fermentation and baking belong to the genus *Saccharomyces*, whose name means "sugar fungus".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] These organisms are cultivated both for their role in generating flavors and aromas considered desirable, and for their ability to inhibit the growth of competing microbes which would otherwise infect food.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Their production of alcohol is linked to their capacity to function with minimal oxygen.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Distilled beverages (also called liquors or spirit drinks) are alcoholic drinks produced by distilling (i.e., concentrating by distillation) ethanol produced by means of fermenting grain, fruit, or vegetables.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Unsweetened, distilled, alcoholic drinks that have an alcohol content of at least 20% ABV are called *spirits*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] For the most common distilled drinks, such as whisky (or whiskey) and vodka, the alcohol content is around 40%.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The term *hard liquor* is used in North America to distinguish distilled drinks from undistilled ones (implicitly weaker).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Brandy, gin, mezcal, rum, tequila, vodka, whisky (or whiskey), baijiu, shōchū and soju are examples of distilled drinks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Distilling concentrates the alcohol and eliminates some of the congeners.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Freeze distillation concentrates ethanol along with methanol and fusel alcohols (fermentation by-products partially removed by distillation) in applejack.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is wine, such as port or sherry, to which a distilled beverage (usually brandy) has been added.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine is distinguished from spirits made from wine in that spirits are produced by means of distillation, while fortified wine is wine that has had a spirit added to it.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Many different styles of fortified wine have been developed, including port, sherry, madeira, marsala, commandaria, and the aromatized wine vermouth.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit, also called "neutral grain spirit", is alcohol which has been purified by means of "rectification" (i.e. repeated distillation).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The term *neutral* refers to the spirit's lack of flavor that would have been present if the mash ingredients had been distilled to a lower level of alcoholic purity.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit also lacks any flavoring added to it after distillation (as is done, for example, with gin).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Other kinds of spirits, such as whiskey, (or whisky) are distilled to a lower alcohol percentage to preserve the flavor of the mash.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Rectified spirit is a clear, colorless, flammable liquid that may contain as much as 95% ABV.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It is often used for medicinal purposes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It may be a grain spirit, or it may be made from other plants.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It is used in mixed drinks, liqueurs, and tinctures, and also as a household solvent.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In the alcoholic drinks industry, congeners are substances produced during fermentation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] These substances include small amounts of chemicals such as occasionally desired alcohols, like propanol and 3-methyl-1-butanol, as well as compounds that are never desired such as acetone, acetaldehyde and glycols.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Congeners are responsible for most of the taste and aroma of distilled alcoholic drinks and contribute to the taste of non-distilled drinks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It has been suggested that these substances contribute to the symptoms of a hangover.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Tannins are congeners found in wine in the presence of phenolic compounds.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add bitterness, have a drying sensation, taste herbaceous, and are often described as astringent.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tannins add balance, complexity, structure and make a wine last longer, so they play an important role in the aging of wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Top-shelf liquor (or "premium liquor") is a term used in marketing to describe higher-priced alcoholic beverages, typically stored on the top shelves within bars.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A mixed drink is a beverage in which two or more ingredients are mixed, and is often alcoholic.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol powder or powdered alcohol or dry alcohol is a product generally made using micro-encapsulation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] When reconstituted with water, the powder becomes an alcoholic drink.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A well drink or rail drink is an alcoholic beverage or mixed drink made using the lower-cost liquors stored within easy reach of the bartender in the bar's "speed rail", "speed rack", or "well", a rack or shelf at a lower level than the bar that the bartender uses to prepare drinks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The average number of people who drink as of 2016 was 39% for males and 25% for females (2.4 billion people in total).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Females on average drink 0.7 drinks per day while males drink 1.7 drinks per day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The rates of drinking varies significantly in different areas of the world.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games are games which involve the consumption of alcoholic beverages and often enduring the subsequent intoxication resulting from them.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Evidence of the existence of drinking games dates back to antiquity.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Drinking games have been banned at some institutions, particularly colleges and universities.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A drinking song is a song sung while drinking an alcoholic beverage.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A beer garden (German: *Biergarten*) is an outdoor area in which beer and food are served, typically at shared tables shaded by trees.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A beer hall (German: *Bierpalast, Bierhalle*) is a large pub that specializes in beer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A cider house is an establishment that sells alcoholic cider for consumption on the premises.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some cider houses also sell cider "to go", for consumption off the premises.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A traditional cider house was often little more than a room in a farmhouse or cottage, selling locally fermented cider.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] An ouzeri (Greek *ουζερί* IPA: [uzeˈri]) is a type of Greek tavern which serves ouzo (a Greek liquor) and mezedes (small finger foods).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Pulquerías (or pulcherías) are a type of tavern in Mexico that specialize in serving an alcoholic beverage known as pulque.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A tiki bar is a themed drinking establishment that serves elaborate cocktails, especially rum-based mixed drinks such as the Mai Tai and Zombie cocktails.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Tiki bars are aesthetically defined by their tiki culture décor which is based upon a romanticized conception of tropical cultures, most commonly Polynesian.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A toddy shop is a drinking establishment seen in some parts of India (particularly Kerala) where palm toddy, a mildly alcoholic beverage made from the sap of palm trees, is served along with food.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A wine bar is a tavern-like business focusing on selling wine, rather than liquor or beer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A typical feature of many wine bars is a wide selection of wines available by the glass.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some wine bars are profiled on wines of a certain type of origin, such as Italian wine or Champagne.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] While many wine bars are private "stand-alone" establishments, in some cases, wine bars are associated with a specific wine retailer or other outlet of wine, to provide additional marketing for that retailer's wine portfolio.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In countries where licensing regulations allow this, some wine bars also sell the wines they serve, and effectively function as a hybrid between a wine shop and a wine bar.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A beer festival is an event at which a variety of beers are available for purchase.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] There may be a theme, for instance beers from a particular area, or a particular brewing style such as winter ales.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Annual wine festivals celebrate viticulture and usually occur after the harvest of the grapes which, in the northern hemisphere, generally falls at the end of September and runs until well into October or later.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] They are common in most wine regions around the world and are to be considered in the tradition of other harvest festivals.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Beer tasting is a way to learn more about the history, ingredients, and production of beer, as well as different beer styles, hops, yeast, and beer presentation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A common approach is to analyze the appearance, smell, and taste of the beer, and then make a final judgment on the beer's quality.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] There are various scales used by beer journalists and experts to rate beer, such as the 1-20 scale used by British sommelier Jancis Robinson and the 1-100 scale used by American sommelier Joshua M.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Professional organizations like the Wine & Spirit Education Trust often rate beer using verbal grades ranging from "faulty" to "outstanding" on a 1-5 scale.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine tasting, on the other hand, is the sensory examination and evaluation of wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] While the practice of wine tasting is ancient, a more formalized methodology has been established since the 14th century.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Modern, professional wine tasters use specialized terminology to describe the range of perceived flavors, aromas, and general characteristics of a wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] More informal, recreational tasting may involve similar terminology, but with a less analytical process and a more general, personal appreciation of the wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Craft beer tourism refers to tourism where the primary motivation of travel is to visit a brewery, beer festival, beer related activity or other event that allows attendees to experience all aspects of the craft beer-making, consuming and purchasing process.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Enotourism, oenotourism, wine tourism, or **vinitourism** refers to tourism whose purpose is or includes the tasting, consumption or purchase of wine, often at or near the source.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Where other types of tourism are often passive in nature, enotourism can consist of visits to wineries, tasting wines, vineyard walks, or even taking an active part in the harvest.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] An apéritif is any alcoholic beverage usually served before a meal to stimulate the appetite, while a digestif is any alcoholic beverage served after a meal for the stated purpose of improving digestion.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wine, liqueurs, and dry champagne are common apéritifs.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Because apéritifs are served before dining, they are usually dry rather than sweet.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] One example is Cinzano, a brand of vermouth.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Digestifs include brandy, fortified wines and herb-infused spirits (Drambuie).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Pure ethanol tastes bitter to humans; some people also describe it as sweet.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] However, ethanol is also a moderately effective solvent for many fatty substances and essential oils.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] This facilitates the use of flavoring and coloring compounds in alcoholic drinks as a taste mask, especially in distilled drinks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some flavors may be naturally present in the beverage's raw material.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Beer and wine may also be flavored before fermentation, and spirits may be flavored before, during, or after distillation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Sometimes flavor is obtained by allowing the beverage to stand for months or years in oak barrels, usually made of American or French oak.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A few brands of spirits may also have fruit or herbs inserted into the bottle at the time of bottling.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine is important in cuisine not just for its value as an accompanying beverage, but as a flavor agent, primarily in stocks and braising, since its acidity lends balance to rich savory or sweet dishes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine sauce is an example of a culinary sauce that uses wine as a primary ingredient.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Natural wines may exhibit a broad range of alcohol content, from below 9% to above 16% ABV, with most wines being in the 12.5–14.5% range.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Fortified wines (usually with brandy) may contain 20% alcohol or more.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar (*vyn egre*; sour wine) is an aqueous solution of acetic acid and trace compounds that may include flavorings.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Vinegar typically contains from 5% to 18% acetic acid by volume.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Usually, the acetic acid is produced by a double fermentation, converting simple sugars to ethanol using yeast and ethanol to acetic acid using acetic acid bacteria.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine and food matching is the process of pairing food dishes with wine to enhance the dining experience.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In many cultures, wine has had a long history of being a staple at the dinner table and in some ways both the winemaking and culinary traditions of a region will have evolved together over the years.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Rather than following a set of rules, local cuisines were paired simply with local wines.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The modern "art" of food pairings is a relatively recent phenomenon, fostering an industry of books and media with guidelines for pairings of particular foods and wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In the restaurant industry, sommeliers are often present to make food pairing recommendations for the guest.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The main concept behind pairings is that certain elements (such as texture and flavor) in both food and wine interact with each other, and thus finding the right combination of these elements will make the entire dining experience more enjoyable.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] However, taste and enjoyment are very subjective and what may be a "textbook perfect" pairing for one taster could be less enjoyable to another.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverages are typical offerings for the folk saint Maximón, and Santa Muerte.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Both folk saints have been described as narco-saints.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A libation is a ritual pouring of a liquid, or grains such as rice, as an offering to a deity or spirit, or in memory of the dead.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It was common in many religions of antiquity and continues to be offered in cultures today.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine or other alcoholic drinks are often used for libation.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Libation was part of ancient Egyptian society where it was a drink offering to honor and please the various divinities, sacred ancestors, humans present and humans who are alive but not physically present, as well as the environment.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It is suggested that libation originated somewhere in the upper Nile Valley and spread out to other regions of Africa and the world.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In the Quechua and Aymara cultures of the South American Andes, it is common to pour a small amount of one's beverage on the ground before drinking as an offering to the Pachamama, or Mother Earth.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] This especially holds true when drinking Chicha, an alcoholic beverage unique to this part of the world.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The libation ritual is commonly called *challa* and is performed quite often, usually before meals and during celebrations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The amount of sacramental wine consumed during the Eucharist is typically limited to a single sip or small portion, which does not result in a measurable increase in the participant's blood alcohol content.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] This controlled and symbolic consumption of the sacramental wine is an integral part of the Eucharistic rite and does not lead to intoxication.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] According to the Catholic Church, the sacramental wine used in the Eucharist must contain alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA) congregations make grape juice available for children and those who are abstaining from alcohol and some will accommodate those with an allergy to wheat, gluten, or grapes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A tincture is typically an extract of plant or animal material dissolved in ethanol (ethyl alcohol).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Solvent concentrations of 25–60% are common, but may run as high as 90%.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In chemistry, a tincture is a solution that has ethanol as its solvent.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In herbal medicine, alcoholic tinctures are made with various ethanol concentrations, which should be at least 20% alcohol for preservation purposes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A flaming drink is often ignited for aesthetic and entertainment purposes.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcoholic beverage may be consumed to celebrate observances such as the International Beer Day, International whisk(e)y day, or National Vodka Day.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] They also drink them for social events like International Women's Collaboration Brew Day, where people come together to make beer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol measurements are units of measurement for determining amounts of beverage alcohol.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol concentration in beverages is commonly expressed as alcohol by volume (ABV), ranging from less than 0.1% in fruit juices to up to 98% in rare cases of spirits.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A standard drink is used globally to quantify alcohol intake, though its definition varies widely by country.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Serving sizes of alcoholic beverages also vary by country.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws regulate the manufacture, packaging, labelling, distribution, sale, consumption, blood alcohol content of motor vehicle drivers, open containers, and transportation of alcoholic drinks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws generally seek to reduce the adverse health and social impacts of alcohol consumption.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In particular, alcohol laws set the legal drinking age, which usually varies between 15 and 21 years old, sometimes depending upon the type of alcoholic drink (e.g., beer vs wine vs hard liquor or distillates).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries do not have a legal drinking or purchasing age, but most countries set the minimum age at 18 years.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some countries, such as the U.S., have the drinking age higher than the legal age of majority (18), at age 21 in all 50 states.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Such laws may take the form of permitting distribution only to licensed stores, monopoly stores, or pubs and they are often combined with taxation, which serves to reduce the demand for alcohol (by raising its price) and it is a form of revenue for governments.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] These laws also often limit the hours or days (e.g., "blue laws") on which alcohol may be sold or served, as can also be seen in the "last call" ritual in US and Canadian bars, where bartenders and servers ask patrons to place their last orders for alcohol, due to serving hour cutoff laws.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In some countries, alcohol cannot be sold to a person who is already intoxicated.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol laws in many countries prohibit drunk driving.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In some jurisdictions, alcoholic drinks are totally prohibited for reasons of religion (e.g., Islamic countries with sharia law) or for reasons of local option, public health, and morals (e.g., Prohibition in the United States from 1920 to 1933).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In jurisdictions which enforce sharia law, the consumption of alcoholic drinks is an illegal offense, although such laws may exempt non-Muslims.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is used in rum-running, the illegal business of smuggling alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Wine fraud relates to the commercial aspects of wine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The most prevalent type of fraud is one where wines are adulterated, usually with the addition of cheaper products (e.g. juices) and sometimes with harmful chemicals and sweeteners (compensating for color or flavor).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Moonshine is illegal to produce and sell in most countries.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In Prohibition-era United States, moonshine distillation was done at night to deter discovery.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Once the liquor was distilled, drivers called "runners" or "bootleggers" smuggled moonshine liquor across the region in cars specially modified for speed and load-carrying capacity.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Outbreaks of methanol poisoning have occurred when methanol is used to adulterate moonshine.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In Australia, a sly-grog shop (or shanty) is an unlicensed hotel, liquor-store or other vendor of alcoholic beverages, sometimes with the added connotation of selling poor-quality products.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Pruno also known as prison hooch or prison wine, is a term used in the United States to describe an improvised alcoholic beverage.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] It is variously made from apples, oranges, fruit cocktail, fruit juices, hard candy, sugar, high fructose syrup, and possibly other ingredients, including crumbled bread.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Most countries have laws specifically for the offense of drunk driving.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Driving under the influence (DUI) or driving while intoxicated (DWI), is the crime of driving a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or other drugs (including those prescribed by physicians).
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Public intoxication laws vary widely by jurisdiction, but include public nuisance laws, open-container laws, and prohibitions on drinking alcohol in public or certain areas.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a common metabolic by-product formed during the breakdown of sugars in many living cells, though it is typically further metabolised to release additional energy.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Certain yeasts constitute an exception, as they excrete alcohol into their environment, where it acts as a chemical defense against competing microorganisms; this role is analogous to that of lactic acid in fermented foods and aromatic compounds in plants.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] While advantageous to yeast, alcohol is toxic to most cells, and in humans its intoxicating effects result from interference with the normal functioning of brain cells.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol is a depressant, which in low doses causes euphoria, reduces anxiety, and increases sociability.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] In higher doses, it causes drunkenness, stupor, unconsciousness, or death.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] A meta analysis of 107 cohort studies concludes low daily alcohol intake provides no health benefits and increased consumption, even at relatively low levels of daily intake (>2 beverages for women and >3 beverages for men), increases health- and mortality-risks.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Short-term effects of alcohol consumption range from a decrease in anxiety and motor skills and euphoria at lower doses to intoxication (drunkenness), to stupor, unconsciousness, anterograde amnesia (memory "blackouts"), and central nervous system depression at higher doses.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Cell membranes are highly permeable to alcohol, so once it is in the bloodstream, it can diffuse into nearly every cell in the body.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Alcohol can greatly exacerbate sleep problems.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] During abstinence, residual disruptions in sleep regularity and sleep patterns are the greatest predictors of relapse.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Long-term use can lead to an alcohol use disorder, an increased risk of developing physical dependence, cardiovascular disease, and several types of cancer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Some nations have introduced alcohol packaging warning messages that inform consumers about alcohol and cancer, as well as fetal alcohol syndrome.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] The addition of warning labels on alcoholic beverages is historically supported by organizations of the temperance movement, such as the Woman's Christian Temperance Union, as well as by medical organisations, such as the Irish Cancer Society.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] WHO estimates nearly half of alcohol-attributable cancers in the WHO European Region are linked to light or moderate drinking defined as "less than 1.5 litres of wine or less than 3.5 litres of beer or less than 450 millilitres of spirits per week".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Public awareness of the link between alcohol consumption and cancer is low in the U.S.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/alcoholic-beverage] Surgeon General argued for the use of cancer warning labels on alcohol products.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2010, the company was purchased by The Griffin Group, an investment and consulting company focused on alcohol brands, and became part of **Anchor Brewers & Distillers, LLC**.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2017, the company was acquired by Sapporo Breweries for US$85 million.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Sapporo's ownership oversaw significant declines in revenue for the brewery, and in 2023, Anchor Brewing ceased operations, with plans to liquidate the business.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In July 2023, Anchor Brewing closed, and its workers attempted to buy out the firm as a worker-owned cooperative.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Instead, on May 31, 2024, Chobani CEO Hamdi Ulukaya announced that he was buying the company and its associated assets.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] He said that he planned to restart the company and keep its operations in San Francisco.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The brewery that would become Anchor was built during the California Gold Rush when Gottlieb Brekle arrived from Germany and began brewing steam beer in San Francisco.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Baruth and his son-in-law, Otto Schinkel Jr., bought the old brewery, creating Anchor Brewing.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] This original location was completely destroyed in the fires that engulfed San Francisco following the 1906 earthquake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] It was rebuilt at a different location in 1907.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] After the deaths of Baruth and Schinkel, the brewery was run by Joseph Kraus and August Meyer until Prohibition forced the brewery to shut down.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] There is no record of what Anchor did during Prohibition, but it resumed operations at a new location once Prohibition in California came to an end in 1933.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] However, the new location burned down in 1944, with Kraus reopening Anchor at another location the same year.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The brewery continued operations through the 1950s, but suffered heavily from the country's increasingly strong preference for beers produced by mega-breweries.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] While there had been more than 4,000 breweries at the turn of the twentieth century, shifts in the industry due to Prohibition and the consolidation of brewing companies meant that only 70 remained by the 1960s.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] As a result of declining sales, Anchor shut down in 1959, but was bought and reopened the following year at a new location by Lawrence Steese.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] By 1965, the brewery was once again suffering from poor sales.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The quality of Anchor's beer had deteriorated under Steese due to a lack of expertise, lack of proper equipment, and poor sanitation standards, which prevented the consistent production of a commercially viable product.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The brewery gained a reputation for producing sour beer, and convincing existing distributors to continue to sell the beer became a challenge.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 1965, Frederick Louis "Fritz" Maytag III bought the brewery, saving it from closure.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Maytag purchased 51% of the brewery for a few thousand dollars, and purchased the brewery outright in 1969.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] By 1971, the brewery began to bottle steam beer (along with other varieties of beer, most notably a Christmas ale) under Maytag's direction.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] He purchased an old coffee roastery on Potrero Hill to serve as Anchor's new location in 1979.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] This building serves as the current location of the brewery.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Turning the failing brewery around required more money than Maytag had from his inherited fortune from the Maytag Company.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Between the initial purchase of Anchor and producing the first batches of bottled beer in 1971, Maytag had to learn the brewing process from scratch, invest in new equipment, and improve sanitation in the brewing process.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The result was a new beer that was a definitive representative of California common beer, but a derivative to the historic steam beer manufactured by Anchor through the previous century.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Before offering in bottles, sales were only as draft beer to thirty local establishments that had long carried the brand.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The bottles were initially sold in four-packs, to keep the price close to mainstream six-packs.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Due to its sale at many local establishments, Anchor's steam beer was well known in the San Francisco area, having a reputation of local importance that grew under Maytag's ownership.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 1977, Arnold Schwarzenegger portrayed an Anchor Brewing employee in an episode of Streets of San Francisco, with Fritz Maytag making a cameo as another employee.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] During the 1980s, Anchor's Steam Beer began to gain national attention and demand increased.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Anchor ultimately served as an early example of a microbrewery, being among the first American breweries to produce porters, barley wine, and India pale ales with regularity.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Its success both regionally and nationally inspired others to enter the brewing business, notably New Albion.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 1989, the company produced a limited beer named Ninkasi, based on a 4000-year-old Sumerian recipe found in an ode to the Sumerian goddess of beer known as the “Hymn to Ninkasi.” The recipe started with a twice-baked bread known as bappir as well as malt and was sweetened with honey and dates.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] It did not include hops or other bittering ingredients, making it considerably sweeter than modern beers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The recipe is described by Charlie Papazian.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Also in 1989, the brewing process for a batch of beer was interrupted during the Loma Prieta earthquake.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The resulting (altered) brew was released as normal Anchor Steam, but with an inverted label; this beer has come to be referred to as *Earthquake Beer*.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 1993, the company opened Anchor Distillery, a microdistillery in the same location as the brewery, and began making a single malt rye whiskey, named *Old Potrero,* after the hill on which the brewery stands.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 1997, the microdistillery began producing a gin, called *Junípero*—Spanish for juniper, and a reference to Fr.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Junípero Serra, an important figure in San Francisco's and California's history.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The distillery also produces a Jenever style gin called Genevieve, using wheat, barley, rye, and the same herbal ingredients as their Junípero gin.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2010, Maytag sold the company to former Skyy vodka executives Keith Greggor and Tony Foglio, from Novato, California, who planned to expand Anchor's business while keeping its commitment to artisan brewing.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2013, the brewery launched Anchor California Lager, a re-creation of a historic Boca Brewing lager from the 1870s.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The brewery also announced a major expansion plan at Pier 48 in the Mission Rock neighborhood near Oracle Park, which would expand Anchor's maximum annual production capacity from 180,000 barrels to 680,000 barrels.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2014, Anchor officially announced Anchor IPA, the first India Pale Ale in the brewery's history.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Anchor ended production of its winter seasonal Bock in 2014 and replaced it a year later with Anchor Winter Wheat.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2017, Anchor was purchased by Sapporo for $85 million.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Working conditions and pay at Anchor had been in a state of decline since Maytag had sold the company, and this trend continued under Sapporo's ownership despite the company's larger holdings.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] This led to further dissatisfaction among the brewery's workers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2018, several workers at Anchor, among them Brace Belden, formed an organizing committee and coordinated with the DSA chapter in San Francisco to develop a plan for unionization with the International Longshore and Warehouse Union.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The unionization efforts were overwhelmingly supported by local bars which served Anchor Steam Beer in the city.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2019, Anchor Brewing workers voted by an almost 2-to-1 margin to join the International Longshore and Warehouse Union making Anchor Brewing – including Anchor Public Taps, the brewery's on-site brew pub – the first unionized craft brewery in the United States.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The three-year union contract was officially ratified in 2020, providing workers with increased wages, health insurance, and other benefits.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2021, Anchor Brewing announced a major makeover of their logo and beer labels.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] On the eve of their 125th birthday, the brewery replaced their vintage-looking labels with a large Anchor logo in a two-tone color schemes per beer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Most labels were not changed in decades or at all.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The design change was met with criticism by consumers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2023, union efforts to renew the existing contract were stalled, with Sapporo delaying negotiations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Soon after, Anchor announced it would no longer distribute nationally and would cease production of its signature Christmas Ale.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] On July 12, 2023, Sapporo announced it was ceasing operations at Anchor and liquidating the business.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Sapporo blamed the closure on decreased sales at restaurants and bars caused by the COVID-19 pandemic, competition from other local brewers, and a shift in consumer preferences to alcoholic beverages other than beer.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Employees were given a 60-day WARN notice on July 12.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] The announcement led to significant outrage from brewery workers, San Francisco bartenders, and locals, with passing drivers chanting "keep brewing" outside the building.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] A spokesman for Sapporo quoted by *The New York Times* said that the firm sought a buyer for Anchor before announcing that the brewery would close, and that it was still possible one might emerge.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] To liquidate Anchor, Sapporo has elected to enter into an alternative to the traditional bankruptcy process known as "Assignments for the Benefit of Creditors".
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Through the process, an "assignee" other than Sapporo will assume stewardship of Anchor and consider bids for the company's assets.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Through this process, a new owner might emerge.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Instead, the founder and CEO of Chobani bought out the company in 2024, with the intention of restarting its operations.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] On May 31, 2024, it was announced that the brewery would be purchased by the founder of Chobani and re-opened.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In February 2025, the new ownership group received the Alcoholic Beverage Control permit required to brew, import, and wholesale beer, as well as import and wholesale wine and spirits.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] However, one year after the announcement, no additional action had been taken.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] Anchor had a year-round range of seven beers, as well as several seasonal beers.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] In 2012, Anchor introduced the Zymaster series, which placed an emphasis on brewing tradition.
[src:anchor-brewing-company/anchor-brewing-company] These beers were generally of an extremely limited nature.
